c name from Middle English <i>mele</i> ‘sand-hill’ (Old Norse <i>melr</i>), as found in such placenames as North Meols, Ravensmeols (both Lancashire), and Great Meols (Cheshire).","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Millman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Meyer, Isadore, Golda, Iren.","English: occupational name for a worker at a mill, from Middle English <i>mille</i>, <i>milne</i> ‘mill’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>mele</i> ‘meal, ground cereal’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’, presumably either a grinder or vendor of meal."]}]},{"name":"Elina","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Late Latin.  See  <b>Éliane</b>   ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Julian","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the common Late Latin name <i>Julianus</i>, a derivative of   Julius .  In classical times <i>Julianus</i> was a name borne not only by various minor early saints, but also by the Roman emperor Julian ‘the Apostate’, who attempted to return the Roman Empire from institutionalized Christianity to paganism. For many centuries the English name <i>Julian</i> was borne by women as well as men, for example by the Blessed Julian of Norwich (  <i>c.</i>1342– after 1413 ). The differentiation in form between <i>Julian</i> and   Gillian   did not develop until the 16th century. <i>Julian</i> is still occasionally used as a girl's name. Notable bearers include the British classical guitarist  Julian Bream  (  b. 1933 ) and the British jazz pianist and bandleader  Julian Joseph  (  b. 1966 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Julyan","meanings":["Modern respelling of   Julian ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":11,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":20,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":31,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":47,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":49,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705210,"age":62,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Elina Julian Meols was born about 1538, in Herefordshire, England. She had at least 1 son with Meals. She died about 1614, in Burton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 78, and was buried in Burton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"abt 1538–abt 1614":"umbes 1538–umbes 1614","1530–1550":"1530–1550","1550–1610":"1550–1610","1538–1614":"1538–1614","1550":"1550","30 May 1614":"30. mai 1614","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","abt 1614":"umbes 1614","abt 1538":"umbes 1538","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","1549":"1549","1538":"1538","1614":"1614","Burton, Cheshire, England":"Burton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, Herefordshire and Worcester, England, United Kingdom":"Herefordshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leominster, Herefordshire,England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bridstow, Ross on Wye, Herefordshire, England":"Bridstow, Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"abt 1538–abt 1614":"noin 1538–noin 1614","1530–1550":"1530–1550","1550–1610":"1550–1610","1538–1614":"1538–1614","1550":"1550","30 May 1614":"30. toukokuuta 1614","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","abt 1614":"noin 1614","abt 1538":"noin 1538","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","1549":"1549","1538":"1538","1614":"1614","Burton, Cheshire, England":"Burton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Herefordshire, Herefordshire and Worcester, England, United Kingdom":"Herefordshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Leominster, Herefordshire,England":"Englanti